Hi Alexandra,

as it happens, I just committed a fairly big redesign of the way in which *opaque* objects are handled in pybind11. See here for details:  http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/latest/advanced.html#treating-stl-data-structures-as-opaque-objects

This change makes it considerably easier to add the ``indexing_suite`` type of utilities to pybind11, and I definitely welcome a PR in this regard. I imagine the resulting code might look something like the following (though you might call the methods differently to make this more pythonic, I guess)

```
template <typename T> void bind_vector_type(const char *name) {
    py::class_<T>(m, name)
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("pop_back", &T::pop_back)
        .def("__len__", [](const T &v) { return v.size(); })
        .def("__iter__", [](T &v) {
           return py::make_iterator(v.begin(), v.end());
        }, py::keep_alive<0, 1>());        
        /* There are multiple versions of push_back(), etc. Select the right ones. */
        .def("push_back", (void (T::*)(const typename T::value_type &)) &T::push_back)
        .def("back", (typename T::value_type &(T::*)()) &T::back);
       /* To be continued :) */
}
```

Thanks,
Wenzel

